      "side": 1,
      "message": "[critical] Line 288: ЁЯФ┤ On Android 12+ (API 31), calling `startService()` from the background can throw `ForegroundServiceStartNotAllowedException` (subclass of `IllegalStateException`). Catching generic `Exception` does handle this, but the intent here is to stop the service тАФ if the service isn\u0027t running, this call is unnecessary and will fail. Consider guarding with a check or using `stopService()` instead of starting with an action, which is more semantically correct and avoids background-start restrictions.\n```suggestion\n            try {\n                stopService(Intent(this, PushForegroundService::class.java))\n            } catch (e: Exception) {\n                Log.w(TAG, \"Can\u0027t stop foreground service\", e)\n            }\n```\nAlternatively, if the ACTION_PUSH_DONE approach is intentional (to allow the service to clean up gracefully), use `startForegroundService()` instead of `startService()` to avoid the background start restriction, but that introduces its own requirement to call `startForeground()` within 5 seconds.",
      "revId": "80e528980c2d03128df2d467c0ffe48d3c8dbc65",
      "serverId": "1e26b4c1-6b8c-47ff-9df7-501b633d3b5a"
